title: Classic TV Serials: The Complete 'Yes, Prime Minister'
description:
Classic TV Serials: The Complete 'Yes, Prime Minister' (Seasons One and Two) 

Yes, Prime Minister is the sequel to Yes Minister. It ran from 1986 to 1988. 

Video size: 512x384 
Audio: 32000hz, 16bps, 2ch 


Series One (1986) 
01. The Grand Design - With his finger now on the nuclear button, Hacker plans his first act as Prime Minister to be a radical new defence policy. 

02. The Ministerial Broadcast - Hacker is groomed for his first television broadcast as PM, but Sir Humphrey is more concerned with the content. 

03. The Smoke Screen - Hacker uses his Health Minister's plan to eliminate smoking as a bluff against the Treasury. 

04. The Key - The PM decides to clip Sir Humphrey's wings when he engages in a territorial battle with Hacker's political advisor. 

05. A Real Partnership - Sir Humphrey has to get through a civil service pay claim while at the same time discrediting its proposer. 

06. A Victory for Democracy - Hacker has difficulty discovering if the Foreign Office is there to carry out government policy or vice versa. 

07. The Bishop's Gambit - A troubled British nurse in Qumran and a vacant bishopric combine to provide an opportunity for Sir Humphrey. 

08. One of Us - The former head of MI5 is revealed to be a spy (despite Sir Humphrey clearing him), while a dog strays on to Salisbury Plain. 


Series Two (1987ÃƒÆ’Ã‚Â¢??88) 
01. Man Overboard - Sir Humphrey fights the Employment Secretary's plan to relocate service personnel by casting doubt over the Minister's loyalty. 

02. Official Secrets - Hacker's attempt to suppress an unflattering chapter of his predecessor's memoirs is leaked to the press. 

03. A Diplomatic Incident - The death of Hacker's predecessor provides a chance for some negotiations with the French over the Channel Tunnel at his state funeral. 

04. A Conflict of Interest - Hacker can avoid a City scandal if he appoints a Bank of England Governor whose honesty isn't beyond reproach. 

05. Power to the People - Sir Humphrey and the leader of Houndsworth Council become strange bedfellows when Hacker tries to reform local government. 

06. The Patron of the Arts - Hacker's invitation to the British Theatre Awards dinner becomes a hot potato when the size of the Arts Council grant is revealed. 

07. The National Education Service - When the Department of Education and Science stands in the way of reform, Hacker decides to abolish it. 

08. The Tangled Web - When Hacker unwittingly lies to the House of Commons he is helped by Sir Humphrey's unfortunate indiscretion.
